SIMPLE: minute
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Minute
<hw>Min"ute</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>minuta</ets> a small portion, small coin, fr. L. <ets>minutus</ets>
small: cf. F. <ets>minute</ets>. See 4th <er>Minute</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The sixtieth part of an hour; sixty seconds.
(Abbrev. <abbr>m.</abbr> or <abbr>min.</abbr>; <as>as, 4 h. 30
<ex>m.</ex></as>)</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Four <qex>minutes</qex>, that is to say, <qex>minutes</qex> of an
hour.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The sixtieth part of a degree; sixty seconds (Marked
thus (⟦prime⟧); <as>as, 10⟦deg⟧ 20⟦prime⟧</as>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A nautical or a geographic mile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A coin; a half farthing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wyclif (Mark xii. 42)</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A very small part of anything, or anything very
small; a jot; a tittle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Minutes</qex> and circumstances of his passion.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A point of time; a moment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I go this <qex>minute</qex> to attend the king.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The memorandum; a record; a note to
preserve the memory of anything; <as>as, to take <ex>minutes</ex> of a
contract; to take <ex>minutes</ex> of a conversation or debate; to read
the <ex>minutes</ex> of the last meeting.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A fixed part of a module. See
<er>Module</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Different writers take as the minute one twelfth, one
eighteenth, one thirtieth, or one sixtieth part of the
module.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Minute
<hw>Min"ute</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a minute or
minutes; occurring at or marking successive minutes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Minute bell</b></col>, <cd>a bell tolled at intervals of
a minute, as to give notice of a death or a funeral.</cd> --
<col><b>Minute book</b></col>, <cd>a book in which written minutes are
entered.</cd> -- <col><b>Minute glass</b></col>, <cd>a glass measuring a
minute or minutes by the running of sand.</cd> -- <col><b>Minute
gun</b></col>, <cd>a discharge of a cannon repeated every minute as a
sign of distress or mourning.</cd> -- <col><b>Minute hand</b></col>,
<cd>the long hand of a watch or clock, which makes the circuit of the
dial in an hour, and marks the minutes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Minute
<hw>Min"ute</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<er>Minuted</er>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <er>Minuting</er>.]</ety>
<def>To set down a short sketch or note of; to jot down; to make a
minute or a brief summary of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Empress of Russia, with her own hand, <qex>minuted</qex> an
edict for universal tolerance.</q> <rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Minute
<hw>Mi*nute"</hw> <pr>(m⟦imac⟧*n⟦umac⟧t" <it>or</it>
m⟦icr⟧*n⟦umac⟧t")</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>minutus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>minuere</ets> to lessen. See <er>Minish</er>, <er>Minor</er>,
and cf. <er>Menu</er>, <er>Minuet</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Very small; little; tiny; fine; slight; slender;
inconsiderable; <as>as, <ex>minute</ex> details</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Minute</xex> drops.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Attentive to small things; paying attention to
details; critical; particular; precise; <as>as, a <ex>minute</ex>
observer; <ex>minute</ex> observation.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Little; diminutive; fine; critical; exact;
circumstantial; particular; detailed.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Minute</er>,
<er>Circumstantial</er>, <er>Particular</er>. A
<xex>circumstantial</xex> account embraces all the leading events; a
<xex>particular</xex> account includes each event and movement, though
of but little importance; a <xex>minute</xex> account goes further
still, and omits nothing as to person, time, place, adjuncts,
etc.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minute-jack</ent>⟦br⟧
